g.text: * user connects wallet, such as MetaMask
data: encode("buy NFT tokenId 456 with 10 USDC")
* encoded transaction is passed to Trails
SDK before it's sent to the wallet for signing
* Trails inspects to see if the transaction will
succeed without enrichment by checking if the wallet
has sufficient funds on the chainId of the required token.
* if there is sufficient funds, Trails just send a normal
* otherwise (as in our example), will continue to find
a reasonable path to complete the transaction execution
* Sequence API leverages Lifi to find
a swap and bridge route on the origin chain
* This is fully pluggable, and can backend to any system
such as Across, the-compact, etc. etc.
* "Solving" is the process of finding a route from origin
to destination to complete the intended transaction
request in the first place on the destination chain.
* The "solution" from the "solver" will consist of computed
transaction calldata that can be bundled in the set of operations
* app queries Sequence Indexer for a user's token
no: txn will fail due to lack of funds,
lets check the wallet for any other tokens
we can use as a means of payment
* user is presented with a simple ui
of tokens per network, balances and prices
* user selects a token, and can either
"cancel" to stop now, or "send" to continue
* client makes request to Sequence Solver API
calldata, for example, on the origin
* encode and pack the set of transactions into a merkletree
of operations encoded as a Sequence v3 intent address
* intent address = merkleroot of 1/1 metamask signer + op1 + op2
* for illustrative purposes, we'll call it 0xIntentAddress
* NOTE: op2 is the intended transaction
the user wanted to make in the first place,
which is to purchase NFT 456 for 10 USDC
* MetaMask pops up (or any wallet), and asks
users confirmation to transfer 25 POL to 0xIntentAddress
* 0.23/POL to 10 USDC + fees is around 25 POL
* YEAY! This is the only wallet confirmation the user has to do!
* client-side SDK in the app notifies the relayers for chain A
and B about the transfer to the 0xIntentAddress,
the set of operations (op1 + op2), and the preconditions for
* precondition for op1 is that 0xIntentAddress on chain A has 25 POL
* precondition for op2 is that 0xIntentAddres on chain B has 10 USDC
* a relayer will execute opX once the precondition X is met
* for more information about preconditions, see ERC7795
* YEAY!! we did it!! a single transfer from MetaMask, and then the Sequence Intent Machine
orchestrates the execution to complete the intended destination transaction.
* The 0xIntentAddress is the result of the computed "solution" which in other words is
the set of operations across multiple chains
* The system is trustless, and if at any point there is a failure, the funds will be
in the 0xIntentAddress, which the MetaMask wallet has full control over, and can
* In practice, the overall process is quite fast, and the slowest portion in the
entire flow is the "solving" part which can certainly be sped up
* Also, technically, the system is 2-clicks, one click to select a payment token
and another click on transaction confirmation with MetaMask.. but, is 1-click on MetaMask side
* NOTE: "Filler" in this case is the bridge operation. As we
use Lifi, they will ultimately provide transaction from a provider
such as Relay, Across, or one of the many bridges out there
